If the model is relatively weak then your uid is going to dereg cause other users want to give it a shot with potentially better solutions, thats a normal behaviour. Emission is divided into roughly top 10 models, with some penalties and mechanisms which prevent from copying top models in straightforward way

Deregistration is inherently caused when a new participant registers, this is behavior that happens across all subnets.
When a new participant registers, the worst performing uid (aka with lowest incentive) will become deregistered. If there exists more than 1 uid with 0 incentive, then there is a specific order of deregistration. Again, this behavior is consistent across all subnets.


This then leads to the question, why did you not receive incentive? The answer is because validators did not grant you enough weights. This too is behavior that is prevalent in all subnets.

Why did validators not assign you weights? If you read the documentation on simulating a validator, you would be able to see the answer. Specifically, your model score is compared against every other miner and a win rate is calculated. To combat blatant model copying, an additional 3% penalty is applied to newer models. If your win rate is high enough compared to other miners, you would receive incentive. However, if your win rate is only average at best, then it is likely you will not receive any significant incentive and will therefore be deregistered according to the protocol. 

None of this behavior is hidden to anyone, it is available on our github and open for all to see and verify. As a miner, you can also run a pseudo validator to verify if validators are setting weights properly.

This is Maja from the white hat validator initiative. We are observing an increasing number of "Broken Pipe" issues across all subnets, affecting validators, miners, and users running scripts and we are trying to determine the root cause of these issues. Are these kind of problems being reported by miners or validators of your subnet?

We strongly suspect that the cause may be related to the general usage of Subtensor. We've noticed that after several repeated attempts to process the same block, it is possible that the Subtensor node temporarily blocks further actions.

Each time you call `metagraph.sync`, it also triggers `subtensor.get_current_block()` and there may be other similar cases. Could you please provide an estimate of the frequency of usage of these functions within your subnet (for miner and validator separately)?
This looks like miners attempting to re-register after deregistration. Investigating

I am the dev for this subnet. For miners, the call to `metagraph.sync` should happen at most once every 24h. For validators, it is every 20m. However, we have not received any reports from either miners or validators regarding this issue yet.

There are two events happening that contribute to this state. 
1. When a miner gets deregistered, their commit data may still persist until a new entry for the respective UID is received. There is no possibility for a new miner to receive the old miner's "score", so the only effect of this is some stale data on the leaderboard
2. The calculation of the model hash is only one part of the duplication check. Another valid criteria is that there must be a _registered_ entry with the model hash. If a miner submitted a model with hash "123456" with `model_hash` as "abcdef", got deregistered, then registered again with the same model, they would not be penalized as the previous entry is not _active_ (because they got deregistered earlier). 

In short, the minerboard occasionally having duplicate data in this case is as expected due to the nature of the bittensor network and how quickly deregistrations are processed. As alluded to in earlier messages, we are working on a new architecture to mitigate deregistration issues in addition to a number of other challenges such as model duplication, submission QoL, etc.

As I mentioned, this is the _minerboard_. When a submission comes in, this is the process:

1. Miner makes `commit` call to bittensor network
2. Model Queue pushes data from the bittensor network to the _leaderboard_ . Note here that the _leaderboard_ and _minerboard_ are related, but separate entities
3. The _minerboard_ is then updated with the hash from the _leaderboard_ and corresponding hotkey, along with other details.
3a. Note that the above operation is update only, meaning that if a miner that got deregistered, and the miner that replaced them did not make a `commit` call _yet_, the older entry will remain in place
3b. The _minerboard_ is simply an association of the miner details (hotkey, block, uid) with the actual scoring data from the _leaderboard_
3c. If you want to check the _leaderboard_, there is another endpoint that should expose this. I am not at my machine right now but it should be findable in the source code.
4. The evaluators process incoming data from the _leaderboard_ and update accordingly


Between steps 3 and 4, it is possible for the _minerboard_ to contain duplicate data but not the _leaderboard_ . The _leaderboard_ uses the `hash` field as a primary key so it is logically impossible to have multiple hashes with the same value. We used to render the _leaderboard_ in the huggingface space, but due to confusion about this process we have switched over to the _minerboard_ for rendering data.

Also to note is that there have been 36 new registrations in the past 24 hours. There are currently 24 models actually in the queue at the moment and it is likely that there will be more submissions, meaning that some race conditions may apply but the deterministic nature of the evaluation will settle any direct `hash` copies/clones. Currently the pruning of old entries is a manual process we look to improve in the future, but this is purely a data synchronization quirk. If you can actually check the data from the bittensor network and find two `hashes` (not model hashes), that would be the actual raise for alarm

I have inspected the data from the metagraph and concluded that this appears to be a bittensor network level behavior that is outside of the control of this subnet in the short term. 
In the metagraph data, it shows that all duplicate submissions were created on the same block. For an attacker/cloner, this would mean they have one of the following attributes:
1. Prior knowledge about the submission (perhaps they are stalking a huggingface account, or some other method outside the scope of this scenario)
2. Actively monitoring the chain and reading from the mempool equivalent for commit data, and copying the commit data

Given 1 is more subjective, let's focus on 2. Suppose an attacker/cloner is actively monitoring the chain for data before it gets published as a block. 
This attacker/cloner would then be able to directly copy another miner's `commit` call data, and even modify and create their own variant of the call data. 
The current mechanism in the other subnets (hashing the hash + miner hotkey) would not be effective in this case, as the attacker can read the call data and decode / re-encode with their hotkey. 
Once the cloned (or modified) call data is made from the attacker/cloner's hotkey, they would have to ensure that this transaction occurs on the same block.
It is not clear if the above is in the realm of possibility. Block times are usually published approximately every ~12 seconds which would give enough time for a script to execute, but at this point we don't know the full dynamics of publishing to the bittensor network.

From this, there are two general scenarios that may be likely:

1. An attacker/cloner is able to accomplish the feat of copying commit data and publishing it in the same block as the original caller. From my knowledge, this appears to be a novel attack and if this is possible, there are larger implications for the bittensor network at large beyond just this specific subnet. 
2. A miner is spamming `commit` calls on different hotkeys and due to some network condition (congestion, race conditions, etc on the bittensor network), their `commit` call is published multiple times in the same block

The current observation is that scenario 2 is much more likely, given this has occurred multiple times for different miners. Another factor that plays into this is that if an attacker/cloner copies the `commit` data, there is no guarantee that the original miner's submission will receive high incentive. It is essentially a bet on another miner, and there is the risk of the original miner's model receiving a low or 0 score that will affect the attacker/cloner as well.
If this is truly the case, then it also means that there is an advantage for the miner as they can receive multiple emissions from the same model, but since they all originate from the same miner the threat for this is minimal.
In the short term, we will allow this. In the long term, we may consider other options depending on how reproducible this scenario actually is.  

If scenario #1 is true, then there is a bigger concern for all subnets that may rely on the `commit` call. There are mitigations available, but this may be something for the bittensor team to investigate
If scenario #2 is true, then we will find a more robust solution down the road.

# On the topic of model copying (and finetuning)

From the activity observed in the subnet, it is evident that as soon as a newly submitted model achieves a high or competitive score, other miners quickly attempt to “copy” or “finetune” the successful model. 

We really do want to encourage miners building on top of and taking ideas from other models in a collaborative fashion, but not what constitutes "leeching" aka blatant copying.
To address this, we have implemented several safeguards (e.g., prohibiting direct repository data copying, performing Hugging Face model hash checks, and applying a 3% penalty for newer models). However, this is an inherently adversarial environment that miners can—and do—exploit.

The fundamental solution would be to develop a formal method that can reliably distinguish between a finetune and a leech. Unfortunately, an efficient computational version of such a method is not yet available, as any proposed solution would need to be applied to every miner submission. To this degree, we have instituted several "soft guards" on this subnet.

Combatting model leeching remains a priority for this subnet, but as mentioned, this issue extends beyond our scope. More broadly, the formal distinction between a “copy” and a “finetune” in the context of developing LLMS is still an emerging topic. This doesn’t even touch on the specific definitions of what constitutes a “copy” versus a “finetune” in the context of LLMs in general and within this subnet specifically. Rest assured, as soon as an effective comparison method becomes available for LLMs, we will implement it swiftly. 

In the meantime, miners can utilize other mitigations, such as protecting against incentive drops with multiple UIDs, relying on the time-based penalty, working with the 48 hour model submission limit, etc. These mitigations have proven to be effective thus far and importantly leads results in what most miners are most likely looking to achieve - emissions consistent with the quality of their model.

The dataset API has two official endpoints:

/dataset There are two required query parameters here:
epoch_date : This is the beginning date for which the older generated data starts from
